{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves the meaning of the source text, not just a word-for-word substitution.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior is about translation quality/semantic adequacy from a neural MT model, not deterministic wiring. Mocking or stubbing would hide the real failure mode (poor/unstable model output). It requires evaluating real model outputs, which can vary across runs/models.","test_description":"Run the service against the real neural translation API on a fixed multilingual evaluation set with human-labeled reference expectations (meaning-preservation and fluency checks or rubric scoring). Fail if quality thresholds are not met.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the translation API returns a 503 error, the service transparently falls back to the dictionary-based translator without returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is module handoff: API client error handling + fallback translator + response shaping. A pure unit test of one function can miss wiring/state propagation bugs. Real external network is not required; a controlled 503 from a stubbed API boundary is sufficient.","test_description":"Start the service with a test SQLite dictionary and an API client double that returns 503. Call the translation endpoint and assert: HTTP/application success to caller, fallback translation returned, and no propagated upstream error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The dictionary-based fallback returns the correct pre-stored translation for phrases that exist in the SQLite database.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Correctness depends on SQL lookup, schema/query mapping, and translator module wiring to SQLite. Mocking DB access can hide real query/collation/encoding issues. No external network/OS subprocess requirement beyond local DB.","test_description":"Create a temporary SQLite DB with seeded phrase pairs, invoke the fallback translator through its service boundary, and assert exact match for stored phrases (including casing/Unicode edge cases relevant to schema).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The quality tracking comparison correctly computes edit distance between primary and fallback outputs and stores the metric.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Although edit-distance math alone is unit-testable, this behavior explicitly includes persistence of the computed metric. Real failure appears at the boundary between computation and storage (wrong field, transaction, or serialization).","test_description":"Use deterministic primary/fallback strings with known edit distances, execute the quality-tracking path end-to-end with test storage, and assert both computed value and persisted record contents (request id/timestamp/value).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When both translators are available, the service returns the primary translation and logs the quality comparison in the background.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is coordination across modules plus asynchronous/background execution. A unit test can miss timing/dispatch/wiring failures between request path and background logger. It does not inherently require real external API behavior or model-quality judgment if translators are de